        <title>The Vietnam War Ends</title>
    </head>
    <body>
        <section class="segment-opener" data-uuid="0125514ed06248668e55cd0d8b98c1cb">
            <article data-uuid="9080e37437c24bf39730c3f2ea6f3a6d">
                <h4 data-uuid="fba06f844097464895f2057ef8c3f3e1">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="8aa4d4a25398492baf64aedad81300b6">The Vietnam War ended in 1973,
                    but it had lasting effects on Vietnam and the United States.</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="10e6bf269aa5485394bf87919e1977b5">The Vietnam War Ends</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="03e7010bdf09490f99156ee2c83f4d27"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="1f84f2f97f894123becf1adb4f001a91">While Nixon was running for re-election in 1972, Henry Kissinger
            continued peace negotiations with the North Vietnamese. On January 27, 1973,
            the United States signed a cease-fire called the Paris Peace Accords with
            representatives of North Vietnam, South Vietnam, and the Vietcong. The United
            States agreed to withdraw all its troops from Vietnam. North Vietnam agreed to
            return all American prisoners of war. Despite the peace agreement, fighting
            broke out between North and South Vietnam in 1974. The United States refused to
            send troops back to South Vietnam.</p>
        <p data-uuid="8282ae41b4774ede9b09e8e73dfbcb39">
            In 1975 North Vietnam invaded the South. Thousands of
            panic-stricken American Embassy workers and South Vietnamese scrambled to
            evacuate Saigon. “The city was in flames,” remembered one American worker. “And
            the Communists had the city surrounded with <br />
            missiles. . . . We realized that we
            were down to hours if not minutes.” Helicopters lifted many people to ships
            waiting off the coast.</p>
